1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,647
Lesson 8 – Monitoring Vendor Performance.

2
00:00:02,647 --> 00:00:06,107
In this lesson, we’ll monitor vendor
performance and contract compliance

3
00:00:06,107 --> 00:00:08,348
during project execution. <break
time="0.5s" />

4
00:00:08,348 --> 00:00:12,392
Once vendor work is underway, the project
needs to make sure it’s delivered as

5
00:00:12,392 --> 00:00:12,760
agreed.

6
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:17,121
Monitoring vendor performance helps the
project confirm that work meets contract

7
00:00:17,121 --> 00:00:19,494
requirements and supports the approved
plan.

8
00:00:19,494 --> 00:00:24,102
It also allows issues to be identified
early, before they become bigger

9
00:00:24,102 --> 00:00:24,695
problems.

10
00:00:24,695 --> 00:00:28,224
This is a core part of maintaining
control in predictive projects. <break

11
00:00:28,224 --> 00:00:28,910
time="0.5s" />

12
00:00:28,910 --> 00:00:32,852
Vendor performance is monitored by
comparing actual work against what was

13
00:00:32,852 --> 00:00:34,111
agreed in the contract.

14
00:00:34,111 --> 00:00:38,128
This includes checking whether
deliverables meet quality standards, are

15
00:00:38,128 --> 00:00:41,170
completed on time, and stay within agreed
cost limits.

16
00:00:41,170 --> 00:00:45,810
Reviews may take place at key milestones
or at regular intervals, depending on the

17
00:00:45,810 --> 00:00:46,325
contract.

18
00:00:46,325 --> 00:00:49,344
The goal is not to manage how the vendor
does the work.

19
00:00:49,344 --> 00:00:53,745
The goal is to confirm that outcomes meet
expectations. <break time="0.5s" />

20
00:00:53,745 --> 00:00:57,878
Monitoring performance also means
monitoring contract compliance.

21
00:00:57,878 --> 00:01:02,508
The project checks that the vendor is
following agreed terms, such as reporting

22
00:01:02,508 --> 00:01:05,773
requirements, approval processes, and
change procedures.

23
00:01:05,773 --> 00:01:09,581
Any work outside the contract must be
formally approved before it begins.

24
00:01:09,581 --> 00:01:13,162
This protects the project from scope
creep and unplanned costs. <break

25
00:01:13,162 --> 00:01:13,889
time="0.5s" />

26
00:01:13,889 --> 00:01:18,232
In some projects, performance
expectations are also supported by

27
00:01:18,232 --> 00:01:20,576
service level agreements, or SLAs.

28
00:01:20,576 --> 00:01:24,739
These define specific performance
measures, such as response times or

29
00:01:24,739 --> 00:01:25,963
availability levels.

30
00:01:25,963 --> 00:01:29,172
They provide another way to monitor
whether vendor services are being

31
00:01:29,172 --> 00:01:31,107
delivered as agreed. <break time="0.5s"
/>

32
00:01:31,107 --> 00:01:36,161
Projects may use inspections, audits, or
performance reviews to assess vendor

33
00:01:36,161 --> 00:01:36,494
work.

34
00:01:36,494 --> 00:01:40,583
These activities help verify that
deliverables meet acceptance criteria and

35
00:01:40,583 --> 00:01:42,903
that contractual obligations are being
met.

36
00:01:42,903 --> 00:01:47,569
Findings from reviews may result in
corrective actions, approved changes, or

37
00:01:47,569 --> 00:01:49,497
formal updates to the contract.

38
00:01:49,497 --> 00:01:53,756
For example, during a system rollout, the
project reviews a vendor’s deliverable

39
00:01:53,756 --> 00:01:55,859
against the agreed acceptance criteria.

40
00:01:55,859 --> 00:01:59,872
The work meets the technical requirements
but is delivered late, prompting the

41
00:01:59,872 --> 00:02:03,988
project to address schedule performance
while still accepting the output. <break

42
00:02:03,988 --> 00:02:04,718
time="0.5s" />

43
00:02:04,718 --> 00:02:05,740
Let’s stop here.

44
00:02:05,740 --> 00:02:10,848
In this lesson, we focused on how vendor
work is monitored during execution.

45
00:02:10,848 --> 00:02:15,067
We also looked at how projects track
vendor performance, check contract

46
00:02:15,067 --> 00:02:18,743
compliance, and use inspections and
reviews to verify outputs.

